Diagnosis.
Males: clypeus subrectangular, apex slightly emarginate (
Fig. 2E
); internal lobe of mandibles strongly sclerotized, mesal brush not crossing the internal lobe (
Fig. 5C
); mentum subtriangular (
Fig. 5F
); labrum slightly prominent at middle, sides round (
Fig. 4G
); small punctures on posterior angles of pronotum with micropunctures between them (
Fig. 2F
); parameres, in ventral view, with apex acute, ventral carina basally acute, inferior edge of parameres round (
Fig. 6H
). Females: clypeus round, punctures deep and coalescent on vertex (
Fig. 7E
); distance from canthi carina to canthi apex larger than canthi thickness (
Fig. 3F
); sensorial area of maxillary palpus rugose (

Fig. 
4I

).
